{"title_page": "Platinum as an investment", "text_new": "[[File:Platinum eagle101.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[American Platinum Eagle]], the official platinum bullion coin of the United States.]]\n\n'''Platinum as an investment''' has a much shorter history in the financial sector than [[gold]] or [[silver]], which were known to ancient civilizations. Experts posit that platinum is about 15\u201320 times scarcer than gold, on the basis of annual mine production. Since 2014, platinum rates have fallen significantly lower than gold rates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.jewelove.in/2016/11/platinum-vs-gold-historical-price.html|title=Platinum v/s Gold \u2013 Historical Price Comparison Chart|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=|access-date=2016-11-27|via=}}</ref> More than 75% of global platinum is mined in [[South Africa]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iii.co.uk/articles/22030/how-trade-platinum-and-palladium|publisher=iii.co.uk|title=How to trade platinum and palladium|accessdate=2015-03-25|first=Nick |last=Louth |date=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[Platinum]] is relatively [[Scarcity|scarce]] even among the [[precious metals]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ptevara.in/about-platinum.php|title=Platinum Evara Jewellery - Gold, White Gold Vs Platinum|publisher=}}</ref>. New [[Mining|mine]] production totals approximately only five million [[troy ounce]]s (150 Mg) a year. In contrast, gold mine production runs approximately 82 million ounces (2,550 Mg) a year, and silver production is approximately 547 million ounces (17,000 Mg).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nymex.com/pla_fut_descri.aspx|title=Futures & Options Trading|publisher=}}</ref>  As such, it tends to trade at higher per-unit prices.\n\nPlatinum is traded on the [[New York Mercantile Exchange]] (NYMEX) and the [[London Platinum and Palladium Market]].  To be saleable on most [[commodity market]]s, platinum [[ingot]]s must be [[metallurgical assay|assay]]ed and [[hallmark]]ed in a manner similar to the way gold and silver are.<ref>[http://www.lppm.org.uk/pgm_good_delivery_cover.html London/Zurich Good Delivery List]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nymex.com/pla_fut_brands.aspx|title=Futures & Options Trading \u2013 Brands of platinum |publisher=NYMEX }}</ref>\n\nThe price of platinum changes along with its [[supply and demand]]; during periods of sustained economic stability and growth, the price of platinum tends to be as much as twice the price of gold; whereas, during periods of economic uncertainty,<ref name=TheSpeculativeInvestor>{{cite web | title = Platinum versus Gold | publisher = The Speculative Invertor | url = http://www.speculative-investor.com/new/article150402.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081026073657/http://www.speculative-investor.com/new/article150402.html | archivedate = 2008-10-26 }}</ref> the price of platinum tends to decrease because of reduced demand, falling below the price of gold, partly due to increased gold prices. Platinum price peaked at US$2,252 per [[troy ounce]] in March 2008 driven on production concerns (brought about partly due to power delivery problems to [[South Africa]]n mines). It subsequently fell to US$774 per troy ounce ($25/g) in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bullion.nwtmint.com/pricing.php|title=Spot Price Charts \u2013 Silver Spot Prices,Gold Prices,Platinum Prices,Palladium Prices|website=nwtmint.com}}</ref> As of 15 October 2018, the platinum spot price in New York was $845.10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apmex.com/spotprices/platinum-price|title=Platinum Prices {{!}} Platinum Price Chart History {{!}} Price of Platinum Today|website=APMEX|language=en|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> per ounce, compared to $1,222 per ounce for gold<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apmex.com/spotprices/gold-price|title=Gold Prices Today {{!}} Price of Gold Per Ounce {{!}} Gold Spot Price Chart|website=APMEX|language=en|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> and $15.16 per ounce for silver<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/commodities/silver-price|title=Silver PRICE Today {{!}} Silver Spot Price Chart {{!}} Live Price of Silver per Ounce {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen.net|work=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>. Platinum is traded in the [[spot market]] with the [[ISO 4217|code]] \"XPT\". When settled in [[United States Dollar]]s, the code is \"XPTUSD\". As of 3/4/2018, the price of platinum has fallen below the price of gold, platinum being valued at US$963 an ounce vis-\u00e0-vis gold at US$1322 an ounce, respectively.<ref>http://www.kitco.com/charts/livegold.html</ref> <ref>http://www.kitco.com/charts/liveplatinum.html</ref> As the cost of platinum per ounce fell, the cost per ounce for other metals in the platinum group - especially Palladium - rose strongly. As of September 2019, Palladium sits at around US$1600 per ounce, compared to US$950 for platinum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bullionbypost.co.uk/platinum-price/week/ounces/USD/|title=Platinum Price in USD per Troy Ounce for Last Week|website=www.bullionbypost.co.uk|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Investment vehicles==\n\n===Exchange-traded products===\n[[File:Platinum prices.png|thumb|Platinum price 1880\u20132011]]\n[[File:Platinum futures prices.png|thumb|Platinum price 1968\u20132012]]\n\nPlatinum is traded as an ETF ([[exchange-traded fund]]) on the [[London Stock Exchange]] under the ticker symbol {{lse2|PHPT}} and on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] as ticker symbols {{NyseSymbol|PPLT}} and {{NyseSymbol|PLTM}}<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Commodity Online |title=ETF Securities to sell Platinum, Palladium shares |url=http://www.commodityonline.com/news/ETF-Securities-to-sell-Platinum-Palladium-shares-27704-3-1.html |date=April 27, 2010 |accessdate=May 10, 2010}}</ref>\nThere are also several ETNs ([[exchange-traded note]]) available,<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Platinum ETF |title=Platinum ETF and ETN list |url=http://www.platinum-etf.net/category/platinum-etf-reviews/ |date=May 15, 2012 |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511233857/http://www.platinum-etf.net/category/platinum-etf-reviews/ |archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref> some of which are inverse to the price of platinum. A list can be found at  [http://etfdb.com/type/commodity/precious-metals/platinum/ ETFDB], [http://etf.stock-encyclopedia.com/category/precious-metals-etfs.html/ stock encyclopedia].\n\n===Platinum coins and bars===\n[[Platinum bar]]s are available from different foundries in different sizes, like 1&nbsp;oz, 10&nbsp;oz, 1&nbsp;kg. [[Platinum coin]]s are another way to invest in platinum, although relatively few varieties of platinum coins have been minted, due to its cost and difficulty in working.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lpm.hk/platinum-palladium.html|title=Buy Platinum, Palladium, and Other Precious Metals {{!}} LPM|website=www.lpm.hk|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> Since 1997, the [[United States Mint]] has been selling [[American Platinum Eagle]] coins to investors. However, commission on prices (for coin, bullion etc.) often renders short-term investments untenable.\n\n===Accounts===\nMost [[Swiss bank]]s offer platinum accounts where platinum can be instantly bought or sold just like any foreign currency.  Unlike physical platinum, the customer does not own the actual metal but rather has a claim against the bank for a certain quantity of metal.\n\n=== Futures ===\nAnother investment option is to create a futures contract where a predetermined time and place is designated to buy or sell the platinum. Unlike options, the transaction is an obligation, and not a right. The [[New York Mercantile Exchange]] (NYMEX) and the [[Tokyo Commodity Exchange]] (TOCOM) trades in platinum futures with a minimum contract size of 50 troy ounces and 500 grams respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barchart.com/futures/quotes/PL*0/profile|title=Platinum Jan '19 (PLF19) Futures Profile - Barchart.com|website=Barchart.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nOther ways of investing in platinum include [[spread betting]] or [[contract for difference|contracts for difference]] on the price of the metal, owning shares in mining companies with substantial platinum assets or exposure, owning traded options in platinum (only available in the US market).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alternative investment]]s\n* [[Gold as an investment]]\n* [[London Platinum and Palladium Market]]\n* [[Palladium as an investment]]\n* [[Silver as an investment]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nymex.com/pla_pre_agree.aspx Information about Platinum as a commodity from New York Mercantile Exchange]\n*[http://www.lppm.org.uk/ London Platinum and Palladium Market]\n\n[[Category:Platinum]]\n[[Category:Precious metals as investment]]\n[[Category:Commodities used as an investment]]\n[[Category:Precious metals]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Platinum eagle101.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[American Platinum Eagle]], the official platinum bullion coin of the United States.]]\n\n'''Platinum as an investment''' has a much shorter history in the financial sector than [[gold]] or [[silver]], which were known to ancient civilizations. Experts posit that platinum is about 15\u201320 times scarcer than gold, on the basis of annual mine production. Since 2014, platinum rates have fallen significantly lower than gold rates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.jewelove.in/2016/11/platinum-vs-gold-historical-price.html|title=Platinum v/s Gold \u2013 Historical Price Comparison Chart|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=|access-date=2016-11-27|via=}}</ref> More than 75% of global platinum is mined in [[South Africa]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iii.co.uk/articles/22030/how-trade-platinum-and-palladium|publisher=iii.co.uk|title=How to trade platinum and palladium|accessdate=2015-